1
00:00:00,066 --> 00:00:01,066
hello everyone

2
00:00:01,066 --> 00:00:03,900
and welcome to yet another ae2 tutorial

3
00:00:03,900 --> 00:00:07,433
to get started, we need to connect our system to a power source

4
00:00:07,433 --> 00:00:09,466
we can do that via an energy acceptor

5
00:00:09,466 --> 00:00:11,566
which will bridge power from other mods

6
00:00:11,566 --> 00:00:15,400
in GTNH, AE2 power consumption can be quite relevant

7
00:00:15,433 --> 00:00:19,166
so I suggest placing the energy acceptor close to your generators

8
00:00:19,166 --> 00:00:22,300
and possibly have some dedicated energy buffer for it

9
00:00:22,600 --> 00:00:24,400
now that our system is powered

10
00:00:24,400 --> 00:00:27,433
we can start giving it a purpose by adding some parts

11
00:00:27,600 --> 00:00:28,900
we start with a drive

12
00:00:28,900 --> 00:00:33,166
which will host up to 10 storage cells to have some inventory capacity

13
00:00:33,166 --> 00:00:34,500
to access this inventory

14
00:00:34,500 --> 00:00:37,100
we can expand our system with a terminal

15
00:00:37,200 --> 00:00:40,633
but that's not the only way of interacting with this inventory

16
00:00:40,933 --> 00:00:42,666
to passively move around items

17
00:00:42,666 --> 00:00:44,666
we have import and export buses

18
00:00:44,700 --> 00:00:49,800
but better yet, we have interfaces, which will keep set amounts of items in place

19
00:00:49,900 --> 00:00:51,500
we also have storage buses

20
00:00:51,500 --> 00:00:55,033
which will allow to directly interact with external storages

21
00:00:55,166 --> 00:00:57,300
but we will see those better later on

22
00:00:57,600 --> 00:01:00,633
the next thing we have to talk about is cables and channels

23
00:01:00,633 --> 00:01:04,900
without a controller, we can only attach up to 8 parts to our system

24
00:01:05,266 --> 00:01:08,000
adding one extra will cause it to collapse

25
00:01:08,233 --> 00:01:09,633
to avoid this limitation

26
00:01:09,633 --> 00:01:14,033
we need to sort out the communication between those parts with the help of a controller

27
00:01:14,466 --> 00:01:19,233
every part we add to our network will require to be connected to our central controller

28
00:01:19,266 --> 00:01:22,300
but cables can only carry a limited amount of connections

29
00:01:22,300 --> 00:01:23,566
more precisely

30
00:01:23,866 --> 00:01:26,900
32 for dense cables and 8 for normal cables

31
00:01:26,900 --> 00:01:28,666
glass cable is the cheapest one

32
00:01:28,666 --> 00:01:30,000
but it can't be painted

33
00:01:30,000 --> 00:01:31,000
which could be a problem

34
00:01:31,000 --> 00:01:34,100
since cable loops can cause unpredictable behaviors

35
00:01:34,333 --> 00:01:36,433
finally we have smart cables

36
00:01:36,500 --> 00:01:37,700
those are more expensive

37
00:01:37,700 --> 00:01:41,366
but will allow you to see the amount of used channels without using any tool

38
00:01:41,666 --> 00:01:43,000
to connect all of your base

39
00:01:43,000 --> 00:01:45,566
you will probably have to reach far places

40
00:01:45,566 --> 00:01:47,966
but long cables could become expensive

41
00:01:48,066 --> 00:01:51,433
to cheap out we can use point to point connections

42
00:01:51,566 --> 00:01:56,066
those things will bridge a cable across two points while using only one channel

43
00:01:56,200 --> 00:01:59,766
meaning they can shrink channel usage by a factor of 32

44
00:02:00,033 --> 00:02:01,766
to set up the P2P bridge

45
00:02:01,766 --> 00:02:05,666
we have to use a memory card to link the input side to the output side

46
00:02:06,100 --> 00:02:09,166
p2ps will however require a channel to work

47
00:02:09,233 --> 00:02:12,033
so we set up a second network just for those

48
00:02:12,300 --> 00:02:14,033
to power that extra network

49
00:02:14,033 --> 00:02:18,400
we can draw some energy from our main network using a piece of quartz fiber

50
00:02:18,866 --> 00:02:22,900
next, we can see how to make our system craft complex items on its own

51
00:02:22,900 --> 00:02:25,900
to do that we start with a pattern terminal

52
00:02:25,900 --> 00:02:29,100
where we can teach the system how to do each crafting step

53
00:02:29,100 --> 00:02:34,000
for example, we can say that one iron dust can be turned into one iron ingot

54
00:02:34,300 --> 00:02:36,300
we encode that recipe into a pattern

55
00:02:36,300 --> 00:02:38,500
which we then move to an interface

56
00:02:38,666 --> 00:02:41,200
that way when the system will need an iron ingot

57
00:02:41,200 --> 00:02:44,500
it will move an iron dust to an inventory near that interface

58
00:02:44,500 --> 00:02:46,700
and accept an iron ingot back

59
00:02:46,800 --> 00:02:49,000
to make the process faster most of the time

60
00:02:49,000 --> 00:02:51,400
you will want NEI to fill up your patterns

61
00:02:51,400 --> 00:02:55,633
and your interfaces to be more compact and dedicated to a single machine

62
00:02:56,033 --> 00:02:58,400
and when using gregtech single blocks

63
00:02:58,400 --> 00:03:02,033
you have to remember to correctly set the machine inputs and outputs

64
00:03:02,233 --> 00:03:05,100
with that I think I covered most of the basic stuff

65
00:03:05,200 --> 00:03:09,100
now let's get into some more advanced stuff typical to GTNH

66
00:03:09,600 --> 00:03:12,766
when dealing with multi blocks, if you don't have unlocked the CIBs

67
00:03:12,766 --> 00:03:16,666
you'll have to split your solids and fluids into two different inventories

68
00:03:16,766 --> 00:03:19,900
a cheap way of doing that is with ingredients buffers

69
00:03:20,033 --> 00:03:23,633
but that solution will cause all sort of issues when scaling up

70
00:03:23,633 --> 00:03:26,800
to fix the speed issues we can use a subnetwork

71
00:03:26,866 --> 00:03:30,300
our interface will drop ingredients into the subnetwork interface

72
00:03:30,300 --> 00:03:34,966
which can only store those inside the storage buses that are attached to the multi block

73
00:03:35,100 --> 00:03:37,200
if you are working with a more expensive machine

74
00:03:37,200 --> 00:03:39,300
and want it to work with different circuits

75
00:03:39,566 --> 00:03:43,466
you can use paint to make sure that ingredients won't react with each other

76
00:03:43,700 --> 00:03:46,266
if instead the issue is that the machine is too slow

77
00:03:46,266 --> 00:03:49,300
you can use P2P interfaces to split the load

78
00:03:49,466 --> 00:03:53,033
to do that, we simply upgrade the interface on our first machine

79
00:03:53,066 --> 00:03:54,566
then like a P2P

80
00:03:54,633 --> 00:03:57,633
we link it to a P2P interface on a second machine

81
00:03:57,733 --> 00:04:01,500
that way we can split craftings across all of the machines we could want

82
00:04:01,566 --> 00:04:04,800
to split the load even better and avoid recipe conflicts

83
00:04:04,800 --> 00:04:08,100
we can add an advanced blocking card to the receiving interface

84
00:04:08,100 --> 00:04:10,566
and turn on blocking mode on the main network one

85
00:04:10,833 --> 00:04:14,433
that will ensure that no items will build up in the input bus

86
00:04:14,466 --> 00:04:17,100
but it could also prevent parallel crafting

87
00:04:17,300 --> 00:04:20,266
we can avoid this side effect by multiplying patterns

88
00:04:20,266 --> 00:04:22,600
or allowing same recipe insertion

89
00:04:22,700 --> 00:04:25,000
and now we can jump to some more complex stuff

90
00:04:25,000 --> 00:04:26,266
assembly lines

91
00:04:26,500 --> 00:04:31,500
as you know the main issue here is splitting all of the ingredients across all of the inputs

92
00:04:31,500 --> 00:04:34,466
to do that you simply use ULV input buses

93
00:04:34,466 --> 00:04:36,633
which can only hold one item stack

94
00:04:36,833 --> 00:04:40,633
and then have decreasing priority on the crafting subnetworks buses

95
00:04:40,833 --> 00:04:45,000
and nowadays this can be easily achieved with a new priority card

96
00:04:45,233 --> 00:04:49,866
in this setup, enabling blocking mode with blocking cards is mandatory to avoid clogging

97
00:04:51,100 --> 00:04:56,166
the only weak point of this setup is recipes that needed the same item in different spots

98
00:04:56,766 --> 00:05:01,966
the mainstream way of fixing that issue is by creating some renamed copies of said item

99
00:05:02,100 --> 00:05:05,100
which can be automated with a rename mold in a press

100
00:05:05,500 --> 00:05:08,033
and now we can move on to more interesting stuff

101
00:05:08,033 --> 00:05:11,000
such as the general purpose advance assembly line

102
00:05:11,266 --> 00:05:12,366
to break it down

103
00:05:12,366 --> 00:05:18,033
let's start by saying that those are 10 identical setups fed by point to point interfaces

104
00:05:18,100 --> 00:05:21,100
so we should focus on just one of those lines

105
00:05:21,166 --> 00:05:22,966
if we check one of those setups

106
00:05:22,966 --> 00:05:30,866
we can see that each row is just an assembly line where each slice is fed whatever item is present in a dedicated subnetwork for this slice

107
00:05:31,266 --> 00:05:34,600
I wanted to highlight that this is just a modular assembly line

108
00:05:34,600 --> 00:05:41,633
where each slice is taking items from an external inventory, shared between all of the assembly lines in the same group

109
00:05:41,633 --> 00:05:46,666
with that you should get that the only challenge is getting each item in a different subnetwork

110
00:05:46,666 --> 00:05:51,233
to do that we create a set of sub networks that can only contain one item type

111
00:05:51,266 --> 00:05:54,433
which can be easily achieved with digital singularity cells

112
00:05:55,233 --> 00:05:58,933
then we place those networks in a way that resembles an assembly line

113
00:05:58,933 --> 00:06:02,566
and feed the that setup the way we will feed an assembly line

114
00:06:02,966 --> 00:06:04,133
to get a better view

115
00:06:04,133 --> 00:06:06,566
here we have our main network interface

116
00:06:06,733 --> 00:06:09,533
dropping into a distribution network interface

117
00:06:09,566 --> 00:06:13,833
which will split ingredients into storage buses according to priority

118
00:06:13,933 --> 00:06:18,566
also every interface must have blocking cards inside and blocking mode enabled

119
00:06:18,866 --> 00:06:23,766
the next thing we should see is how to build a controller with a lot of usable channels

120
00:06:23,933 --> 00:06:25,100
before we get started

121
00:06:25,100 --> 00:06:27,633
I would like to tell you that this is not required

122
00:06:27,700 --> 00:06:31,500
I have used about 100 controller faces to complete the stargate

123
00:06:31,500 --> 00:06:34,400
and that can be easily achieved by basic layouts

124
00:06:34,700 --> 00:06:40,166
with that I mean that this simple controller here is already providing as many channels as I used to build a star gate

125
00:06:40,166 --> 00:06:43,066
and there is still plenty of unused space

126
00:06:43,500 --> 00:06:47,266
anyways the way I built my controller is more or less like this

127
00:06:47,333 --> 00:06:49,700
we start with a controller shell done like that

128
00:06:49,700 --> 00:06:52,500
and then we add P2P all over the inner side

129
00:06:52,500 --> 00:06:56,066
we add two wireless connectors to take out those P2P connection

130
00:06:56,066 --> 00:06:58,333
and complete the controller cell like that

131
00:06:58,333 --> 00:07:01,666
we take out each one of the wireless connector to an open space

132
00:07:01,666 --> 00:07:05,066
where we build a wall for all of the P2P that will be bridged

133
00:07:05,400 --> 00:07:09,366
connect all of the P2Ps of the controller with the P2Ps on the wall

134
00:07:09,500 --> 00:07:14,966
finally, we add the easily accessible wireless connector that we will be using for our base

135
00:07:15,666 --> 00:07:17,466
I didn't go much into the details

136
00:07:17,466 --> 00:07:20,966
because I think I should first figure out a proper way of editing videos

137
00:07:21,100 --> 00:07:25,666
and I think there are already plenty of good tutorials on YouTube on how to do those things

138
00:07:26,033 --> 00:07:29,766
so I just try to showcase the most useful or interesting stuff

139
00:07:29,766 --> 00:07:31,100
before I do anything else

140
00:07:31,100 --> 00:07:35,500
I'd first want to know if I should go back to the text to speech or keep using my voice

141
00:07:35,600 --> 00:07:36,366
but ideally

142
00:07:36,366 --> 00:07:38,966
to ease editing and be closer to my preferred style

143
00:07:38,966 --> 00:07:42,066
I would like to not have to type a script, and just improvise

144
00:07:42,166 --> 00:07:47,700
but most importantly, I think that you should just test out whatever you want instead of blindly following a tutorial

145
00:07:47,700 --> 00:07:53,800
and for that reason I will often reply "why" questions with "why not?" or "go and try yourself to find out"

146
00:07:53,866 --> 00:07:55,100
I don't want to be mean

147
00:07:55,100 --> 00:07:58,900
I just want to say that the best way of learning is by trial and error

148
00:07:59,366 --> 00:08:00,066
for the next video

149
00:08:00,066 --> 00:08:03,866
I will probably try to show answer to whatever questions I get in the comments

150
00:08:03,900 --> 00:08:05,166
see you next time

151
00:08:05,166 --> 00:08:05,700
bye bye

152
00:00:00,066 --> 00:00:01,066
大家好

153
00:00:01,066 --> 00:00:03,900
欢迎来到又一个 AE 教程

154
00:00:03,900 --> 00:00:07,433
首先，我们需要给 AE 系统供电

155
00:00:07,433 --> 00:00:09,466
我们可以通过能源接收器来做到这一点

156
00:00:09,466 --> 00:00:11,566
它能将其他mod的电源转换为AE电

157
00:00:11,566 --> 00:00:15,400
在GTNH中，给AE供电相当重要

158
00:00:15,433 --> 00:00:19,166
所以我建议把能源接收器放在靠近发电机的地方

159
00:00:19,166 --> 00:00:22,300
并且尽量放一些专门的能量缓存

160
00:00:22,600 --> 00:00:24,400
现在我们的系统通电了

161
00:00:24,400 --> 00:00:27,433
我们可以通过添加一些部分给它事干

162
00:00:27,600 --> 00:00:28,900
我们从驱动器开始

163
00:00:28,900 --> 00:00:33,166
它将容纳多达10个存储单元以具有库存容量

164
00:00:33,166 --> 00:00:34,500
要访问此库存

165
00:00:34,500 --> 00:00:37,100
我们可以用终端扩展我们的系统

166
00:00:37,200 --> 00:00:40,633
但这并不是与库存交互的唯一方式

167
00:00:40,933 --> 00:00:42,666
要被动地移动物品

168
00:00:42,666 --> 00:00:44,666
我们有输入总线和输出总线

169
00:00:44,700 --> 00:00:49,800
但更好的是，我们有ME接口，它将维持一定数量的物品

170
00:00:49,900 --> 00:00:51,500
我们还有存储总线

171
00:00:51,500 --> 00:00:55,033
这将允许与外部存储直接交互

172
00:00:55,166 --> 00:00:57,300
但我们最好稍后再看它们

173
00:00:57,600 --> 00:01:00,633
接下来我们要谈的是线缆和频道

174
00:01:00,633 --> 00:01:04,900
如果没有控制器，我们最多只能将8个部件连接到AE上

175
00:01:05,266 --> 00:01:08,000
再添加一个部件会导致系统崩溃

176
00:01:08,233 --> 00:01:09,633

为了避免这种局限


177
00:01:09,633 --> 00:01:14,033

我们需要在ME控制器的帮助下解决这些部分之间的通信


178
00:01:14,466 --> 00:01:19,233
我们添加到网络中的每个部分都需要连接到中央控制器

179
00:01:19,266 --> 00:01:22,300
但是线缆只能承载有限数量的连接

180
00:01:22,300 --> 00:01:23,566
更准确地说

181
00:01:23,866 --> 00:01:26,900
密集线缆能承载32个频道，普通线缆8个

182
00:01:26,900 --> 00:01:28,666
玻璃线是最便宜的

183
00:01:28,666 --> 00:01:30,000
但是无法被染色

184
00:01:30,000 --> 00:01:31,000
这可能是个问题

185
00:01:31,000 --> 00:01:34,100
因为线缆环路会导致不可预测的行为

186
00:01:34,333 --> 00:01:36,433
最后是智能线缆

187
00:01:36,500 --> 00:01:37,700
那玩意很贵

188
00:01:37,700 --> 00:01:41,366
但可以让你在不使用任何工具的情况下查看使用的频道数量

189
00:01:41,666 --> 00:01:43,000
要连接整个基地

190
00:01:43,000 --> 00:01:45,566
你可能拉线缆到很远的地方

191
00:01:45,566 --> 00:01:47,966
但长线缆可能会变得昂贵

192
00:01:48,066 --> 00:01:51,433
为了省钱，我们可以使用p2p

193
00:01:51,566 --> 00:01:56,066
这东西只用一个通道就能将两条线缆连接

194
00:01:56,200 --> 00:01:59,766
这意味着他们可以将频道使用量减少32倍

195
00:02:00,033 --> 00:02:01,766
要建立P2P连接

196
00:02:01,766 --> 00:02:05,666
我们必须使用内存卡将输入端链接到输出端

197
00:02:06,100 --> 00:02:09,166
然而，p2p需要一个通道才能工作

198
00:02:09,233 --> 00:02:12,033
所以我们为此建立了第二个网络

199
00:02:12,300 --> 00:02:14,033
为了给这个额外的网络供电

200
00:02:14,033 --> 00:02:18,400
我们可以用一个石英纤维从主网络中汲取一些能量

201
00:02:18,866 --> 00:02:22,900
接下来，我们可以看看如何让系统自己制作复杂的物品

202
00:02:22,900 --> 00:02:25,900
为此，我们从样板终端开始

203
00:02:25,900 --> 00:02:29,100
在那里我们可以教系统如何完成每个制作步骤

204
00:02:29,100 --> 00:02:34,000
例如，我们可以说一个铁粉可以变成一个铁锭

205
00:02:34,300 --> 00:02:36,300
我们将配方编码为样板

206
00:02:36,300 --> 00:02:38,500
然后我们把它放到ME接口

207
00:02:38,666 --> 00:02:41,200
这样当系统需要一个铁锭时

208
00:02:41,200 --> 00:02:44,500
它会将铁粉移动到ME接口附近的库存中

209
00:02:44,500 --> 00:02:46,700
并接受一个铁锭的返回

210
00:02:46,800 --> 00:02:49,000
多数情况下，要让处理的速度更快

211
00:02:49,000 --> 00:02:51,400
一般会用NEI写样板

212
00:02:51,400 --> 00:02:55,633
并且让ME接口更加紧凑并专用于单台机器

213
00:02:56,033 --> 00:02:58,400
在使用GT单方块机器时

214
00:02:58,400 --> 00:03:02,033
你必须记住正确设置机器输入和输出

215
00:03:02,233 --> 00:03:05,100
有了这个，我想我涵盖了大部分基本的东西

216
00:03:05,200 --> 00:03:09,100
现在让我们进入一些GTNH特有的更高级的东西

217
00:03:09,600 --> 00:03:12,766
在自动化多方块时，如果你没有解锁样板输入总成

218
00:03:12,766 --> 00:03:16,666
你必须把物品和流体分别输入两个不同的仓室

219
00:03:16,766 --> 00:03:19,900
一种便宜的方法是使用原材料缓存仓

220
00:03:20,033 --> 00:03:23,633
但该解决方案在扩展时会导致各种问题

221
00:03:23,633 --> 00:03:26,800
为了解决速度问题，我们可以使用子网

222
00:03:26,866 --> 00:03:30,300
主网的ME接口会将材料送入子网的ME接口

223
00:03:30,300 --> 00:03:34,966
子网的ME接口只能将那些材料存储在
贴着多方块机器的仓室的存储总线内

224
00:03:35,100 --> 00:03:37,200
如果你使用的是更昂贵的机器

225
00:03:37,200 --> 00:03:39,300
并希望它能同时使用不同的编程电路

226
00:03:39,566 --> 00:03:43,466
你可以给仓室染色以确保不会串配方

227
00:03:43,700 --> 00:03:46,266
如果问题是机器太慢了

228
00:03:46,266 --> 00:03:49,300
你可以使用P2P接口来分配负载

229
00:03:49,466 --> 00:03:53,033
为此，我们只需把一台机器上的ME接口升级成p2p的

230
00:03:53,066 --> 00:03:54,566
然后像P2P一样

231
00:03:54,633 --> 00:03:57,633
我们将其连接到第二台机器上的P2P接口

232
00:03:57,733 --> 00:04:01,500
这样我们就可以把合成均摊到我们想要的所有机器

233
00:04:01,566 --> 00:04:04,800
为了更好地分配负载并避免配方冲突

234
00:04:04,800 --> 00:04:08,100
我们可以在接收端的ME接口中添加高级阻挡卡

235
00:04:08,100 --> 00:04:10,566
并在主网的ME接口里打开阻挡模式

236
00:04:10,833 --> 00:04:14,433
这将确保输入总线中不会堆积任何物品

237
00:04:14,466 --> 00:04:17,100
但它也会限制机器并行

238
00:04:17,300 --> 00:04:20,266
我们可以通过倍增样板来避免这个副作用

239
00:04:20,266 --> 00:04:22,600
或允许输入相同的配方

240
00:04:22,700 --> 00:04:25,000
现在我们可以跳到一些更复杂的东西

241
00:04:25,000 --> 00:04:26,266
也就是——装配线

242
00:04:26,500 --> 00:04:31,500
如你所知，这里的主要问题是在所有输入中均分材料

243
00:04:31,500 --> 00:04:34,466
为此，你只需使用ULV输入总线

244
00:04:34,466 --> 00:04:36,633
它只能容纳一组的物品

245
00:04:36,833 --> 00:04:40,633
然后在子网的存储总线上逐渐降低优先级

246
00:04:40,833 --> 00:04:45,000
如今，这操作可以通过优先卡轻松实现

247
00:04:45,233 --> 00:04:49,866
在这套自动化中，必须使用阻挡卡
并启用阻挡模式，以避免原料堆积

248
00:04:51,100 --> 00:04:56,166
这个设置的唯一弱点是
在不同的地方需要相同物品的配方

249
00:04:56,766 --> 00:05:01,966
解决这个问题的主流方法是创建
所述物品的一些重命名副本

250
00:05:02,100 --> 00:05:05,100
重命名可以通过压模机中的重命名模具实现自动化

251
00:05:05,500 --> 00:05:08,033
现在我们可以继续更有趣的事情了

252
00:05:08,033 --> 00:05:11,000
比如通用高级装配线

253
00:05:11,266 --> 00:05:12,366
要拆开、揉碎了讲

254
00:05:12,366 --> 00:05:18,033
首先，这是由p2p接口提供的10个相同的设置

255
00:05:18,100 --> 00:05:21,100
所以我们应该只关注其中一条装配线

256
00:05:21,166 --> 00:05:22,966
如果我们检查其中一个设置

257
00:05:22,966 --> 00:05:30,866

我们可以看到，这就是个常规的装配线
其中每一层都在被动抽取该层的专用子网中存在的东西


258
00:05:31,266 --> 00:05:34,600
我想强调的是，这就是一条模块化的装配线

259
00:05:34,600 --> 00:05:41,633
其中每一层从外部库存中取出物品
这个库存是在同组的所有装配线之间共享的

260
00:05:41,633 --> 00:05:46,666
这样说完，你应该明白唯一的挑战是
将每个物品放在不同的子网中

261
00:05:46,666 --> 00:05:51,233
为此，我们创建了一系列只能包含一种物品的子网

262
00:05:51,266 --> 00:05:54,433
这可以通过数字奇点元件轻松实现

263
00:05:55,233 --> 00:05:58,933
然后我们将这些网络以类似于装配线的方式放置

264
00:05:58,933 --> 00:06:02,566
并按照之前自动化装配线的方式给该设置输入物品

265
00:06:02,966 --> 00:06:04,133
为了看得更清楚

266
00:06:04,133 --> 00:06:06,566
这是我们的主网ME接口

267
00:06:06,733 --> 00:06:09,533
输入物品到用于分配原料的子网的ME接口

268
00:06:09,566 --> 00:06:13,833
子网ME接口会根据优先级将原料输入存储总线

269
00:06:13,933 --> 00:06:18,566
存储总线对着的ME接口内部
都必须有阻挡卡并启用阻挡模式

270
00:06:18,866 --> 00:06:23,766
接下来我们看看如何构建一个
具有大量可用频道的ME控制器

271
00:06:23,933 --> 00:06:25,100
在我们开始之前

272
00:06:25,100 --> 00:06:27,633
我想告诉你这不是必须的

273
00:06:27,700 --> 00:06:31,500
我用了大约100个ME控制器的面来完成星门

274
00:06:31,500 --> 00:06:34,400
这可以通过基本布局轻松实现

275
00:06:34,700 --> 00:06:40,166
我的意思是这个简单的控制器已经提供了
和我用来建造星门一样多的频道

276
00:06:40,166 --> 00:06:43,066
而且还有大量未使用的空间

277
00:06:43,500 --> 00:06:47,266
无论如何，我构建控制器的方式大概是这样的：

278
00:06:47,333 --> 00:06:49,700
我们从这样的控制器外壳开始

279
00:06:49,700 --> 00:06:52,500
然后在内侧添加P2P

280
00:06:52,500 --> 00:06:56,066
添加两个无线连接器来引出那些P2P通道

281
00:06:56,066 --> 00:06:58,333
并像那样完成控制器单元

282
00:06:58,333 --> 00:07:01,666
我们将无线连接器连到到一个开放空间

283
00:07:01,666 --> 00:07:05,066
为所有被桥接的P2P建立一堵墙

284
00:07:05,400 --> 00:07:09,366
将控制器的所有P2P与墙上的P2P连接起来

285
00:07:09,500 --> 00:07:14,966
最后，我们添加易于访问的无线连接器
我们用它们联通整个基地

286
00:07:15,666 --> 00:07:17,466
我没说太多细节

287
00:07:17,466 --> 00:07:20,966
因为我想我做得合适视频剪辑

288
00:07:21,100 --> 00:07:25,666
我认为YouTube上已经有很多关于AE的好教程

289
00:07:26,033 --> 00:07:29,766
所以我只是想展示最有用或最有趣的东西

290
00:07:29,766 --> 00:07:31,100
在我做其他事情之前

291
00:07:31,100 --> 00:07:35,500
我首先想知道我是应该回到ai配音还是继续使用我的声音

292
00:07:35,600 --> 00:07:36,366
但理想情况下

293
00:07:36,366 --> 00:07:38,966
为了简化剪辑并更接近我喜欢的风格

294
00:07:38,966 --> 00:07:42,066
我希望不写剧本，就即兴发挥

295
00:07:42,166 --> 00:07:47,700
但最重要的是，我认为对于任何你想做的事情
应该先去试一试，而不是盲目地跟教程走

296
00:07:47,700 --> 00:07:53,800
出于这个原因，我经常会用"为什么不呢"
或者"去试试看"来回答"为什么"的问题

297
00:07:53,866 --> 00:07:55,100
我没有任何贬低的意思

298
00:07:55,100 --> 00:07:58,900
我只想说最好的学习方法是通过试验和排除错误

299
00:07:59,366 --> 00:08:00,066
对于下一个视频

300
00:08:00,066 --> 00:08:03,866
我可能会试着回答评论区中的问题

301
00:08:03,900 --> 00:08:05,166
下次见

302
00:08:05,166 --> 00:08:05,700
拜拜

303
00:01:00,633 --> 00:01:04,900
（一个部件占用一个频道）

304
00:03:16,766 --> 00:03:19,900
(它能同时存储物品和流体）

305
00:06:27,700 --> 00:06:31,500
（一个面能提供32个频道）

306
00:07:31,100 --> 00:07:35,500
（现在他决定给速通类的视频三个音轨
口播英语、口播意大利、ai英语
其他类型的视频应该就只有口播英语）

307
00:08:00,066 --> 00:08:03,866
（他之后并没有做这个）

